'''Lucille Roubedeaux''' (died 2005)<ref name="endangeredlanguages">{{cite web|url=http://www.endangeredlanguages.com/lang/osa|title=Endangered Languages Project - Osage|publisher=endangeredlanguages.com|accessdate=2015-08-16}}</ref><ref name="typepad">{{cite web|url=http://ageoftheosage.typepad.com/blog/2011/09/words-of-the-tribe.html|title=Words of the Tribe - Age of the Osage|publisher=ageoftheosage.typepad.com|accessdate=2015-08-16}}</ref> was the [[terminal speaker|final surviving native speaker]] of the [[Osage language]] of [[Oklahoma]]. A program had been initiated to revive the language before the death of the last speaker, but to not much avail: "This is the last train out. If we can't get it done this time around, then that's it. There is no more after this. That's it," said "Uncle Mogre" of the Osage who had been working to preserve the language.<ref name="upenn">{{cite web|url=http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?cat=83&paged=2|title=Language Log &raquo; Endangered languages|publisher=languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu|accessdate=2015-08-16}}</ref> At the time of Mrs. Roubedeaux's death, the Osage language had been dwindling for nearly 200 years.<ref name="upenn2">{{cite web|url=http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=2203|title=Language Log &raquo; Talking Osage|publisher=languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu|accessdate=2015-08-16}}</ref>

