{{Expand Dutch|Stephanie Vetter|date=February 2015}} '''Johanna Maria Stephanie Claes-Vetter''' (February 25, 1884 &ndash; October 9, 1974) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-born novelist in [[Belgium]] who wrote in [[Dutch language|Dutch]].<ref name=bio/>
She was born '''Johanna Maria Stephanie Vetter''' in [[Zutphen]] and married Flemish writer [[Ernest Claes]]. Vetter was an advocate for women's rights in [[Flanders]]. From 1909 to 1914, she was co-editor of the women's literary magazine ''De Lelie''. She published her first novel ''Eer de mail sluit'' (Before the mail closes) in 1915. In 1927, a collection of short stories ''Verholen krachten'' (Hidden forces) was published.<ref name=bio>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=2Wf1SVbGFg8C&pg=PA256 |title=An Encyclopedia of Continental Women Writers |pages=256–57 |year=1991 |ISBN=0824085477 |last=Wilson |first=Katharina M |volume=Volume 1}}</ref>
She died in [[Elsene]] at the age of 90.<ref name=bio/>
== Selected works<ref name=bio/> == * ''Als de dagen lengen'' (When the days lengthen) (1940) * ''Haar eigen weg'' (Her own way) (1944) * ''Martine - een ontgoocheling'' (Martine - a disappointment) (1954) * ''Angst'' (1960)
